===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|牛|丄|t1=cattle|t2=|ls=ic}}. Various explanations exist, some propose 丄 (here unrelated to {{zh-l|*上}}) depicts a penis to represent “male”. Later 丄 came to be written {{zh-l|*土}}. See also the etymology of this character.

===Etymology===
{{der|zh|aav}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}). Compare {{cog|mkh-pro|*ɟm(oo)l||male}} (whence {{cog|km|ឈ្មោល||to be male}}), {{cog|omx|jmur|jmūr ~ jmur|male (elephant)}}, Proto-{{w|Waic languages|Waic}} {{m|und|*(k)mɔj||(wild) ox; buffalo}}, {{cog|mkh-vie-pro|*mɔːlʔ||person; human being}} (whence {{cog|vi|mọi||savage; barbarian}}, {{cog|mtq|mõl||human being}}).

An {{w|oracle bone script|oracle bone}} graph for this word shows a vertical stick on a horizontal ground, possibly because it had been intended for an obsolete homophone cognate with {{cog|mkh-vie-pro|*c-mɔːlʔ||digging stick}}, which alongside "male" may derive from a stem represented in {{cog|okz|cval||to enter; to penetrate; (of animals) to copulate}}, {{cog|kjg|tr=cmɔɔl|t=to plant (rice) with a digging stick}}, {{m|kjg|tr=crmɔɔl|t=digging stick}} ([[ibid.]]; {{zh-ref|Ferlus, 1987}}). {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} further proposes a relationship with {{och-l|畝|cropland; mu (a Chinese measuring unit for area)}} ([[ibid.]]); see there for more.

